RED FLAG 8 — BDL/BQL handling
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

Symptom: BDL (Below Detection Limit) entries have converted_ppm = null. 
Calculator treats as unresolved, computes 0 exposure. Scientifically wrong 
for worst-case assessment.

Fix in process_rs_annexure:
When raw_value in ("BDL", "BQL", "ND", "Not detected", "< LOD", "< LOQ"):
- If entry has associated NMT spec limit in raw_text (from same table row)
- Use spec limit as converted_ppm for worst-case exposure
- Set evidence_type = "nmt", calculation_basis = "nmt_conservative_bdl"
- Add audit note: "BDL result; using spec limit for worst-case exposure"

Universal rule. Applies to any solvent, any annexure.

Acceptance:
- Acetone BDL with NMT 5000 → converted_ppm = 5000
- DCM BDL with NMT 600 → converted_ppm = 600
- IPA BQL with NMT 5000 → converted_ppm = 5000

